article.description:
Antawn Jamison scored 34 points Wednesday night to help the Washington Wizards hand the Memphis Grizzlies a
103-91 loss in the first regular-season game at the new FedExForum.
article.headline: Wizards win despite suiting up just eight
article.linkText: Strong third quarter, Jamison's 34 leads Wizards
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Eight players was quite enough for the Washington Wizards to spoil the Memphis Grizzlies' opening night at their new $250 million arena. The Wizards, led by Antawn Jamison's 34 points, had just eight players in uniform due to injuries and suspensions, but still beat the Grizzlies 103-91 Wednesday night in the season opener for both teams. The Wizards were without Brendan Haywood, Larry Hughes, Anthony Peeler and Gilbert Arenas. Haywood and Hughes were suspended for a fight during the preseason. Arenas was out because of a handgun violation, and Peeler was suspended for an elbow jab during last season's playoffs. "We should have got this game," Bonzi Wells said. "They were short-handed, missing three or four of their best guys, and we still got beat." A sellout crowd of 18,119 came out to the Grizzlies' FedExForum, the promised arena that lured the franchise from Vancouver. The team played at the Memphis Pyramid their first three seasons in Tennessee while the new arena was being built. "Everybody thought we were supposed to get blown out," said Washington's Jarvis Hayes. "They won 50 games (last year) and they're opening a new arena, so we weren't supposed to win this game. But we did." The Wizards got 28 points from Juan Dixon, while Hayes added 20 points and nine rebounds. Laron Profit added 11 points for Washington. The Grizzlies opened strong and held a 52-44 advantage at halftime. But the Wizards outscored Memphis 32-11 in the third period to take control for good. The Grizzlies shot 5-of-23 from the field in the period. "They came out and hit everything," said Wells, who started in place of an ailing Mike Miller. "We weren't playing good defense. We weren't rebounding the ball." Miller has been bothered by back trouble, but Memphis coach Hubie Brown said he started Wells just to try something new with the lineup. Shane Battier said the Grizzlies lacked the passion that resulted in a 50-win season last year. "That's what you call an old-fashion butt kicking," Battier said. "We didn't deserve to win that game. We were outplayed." Michael Ruffin, who started at center for the Wizards in place of the suspended Haywood, had 11 rebounds and a career-high seven blocks for Washington. Pau Gasol added 17 points and nine rebounds for Memphis, and Stromile Swift had 15 points and eight rebounds. Brian Cardinal, who signed as a free agent in the offseason, had 13 points.

Game notes
Memphis' Lorenzen Wright was also suspended for fighting during the preseason. ... NBA Commissioner David Stern and Grizzlies owner Michael Heisley welcomed the fans during a brief ceremony marking the first regular season game in the new arena.<
